713914f-a.text:
W. 57th Street (right), west from Eighth Avenue (foreground, not shown) as viewed from atop the Fisk Bldg., between the latter point and Broadway. Shown is a general view of the surrounding west side, an area formerly known as San Juan Hill. In the background is the North (Hudson) River and the Jersey Shore. Note that at this date the last 1OOO foot pier appears to be near 46th Street. To the right one sees Roosevelt Hospital, Dewitt Clinton High School and the New York Central Railroad Yards. Radical changes in the foreground to the east of Ninth Avenue will be the Parc Vendome Apartments and the American Womens' Association Building.
May 1926.
Brown Mros.

713921f-a.text:
355-309 West 57th Street, north side, between Ninth and Eighth AVes. At the extreme left is the new American Women's Association Building. The apartment house at the extreme right replaced the Protestant Episcopal Church of the Strangers. The view is northeastward from clearance (present site of Parc Vendome Apartments) on the south side of the
street and between the aforementioned Aves.
January 9, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.
The New York Times of March 13, 1940 reports the sale of a site known as No. 331-45 West 57th Street and 334-46 West 58th Street. Two eight-story apartments will be constructed here constituting a project with frontages of 160 feet on the former thoroughfare and 137 on the latter. This is directly opposite the Parc Vendome Apartments and half a block east of the A. W. A. Bldg.

713910f-a.text:
West 57th Street, north side, east from a point (No. 319, left) to the west of Eighth Avenue, across same to Broadway (extreme right). Silhouetted against the new General Motors Bldg. is the Church of the Strangers (P.E.) at No. 309 W. 57th Street. This structure, built as a memorial to Dr. Charles F. Deems in 1870 by the Universalist Church of Our Saviour, vas sold to the present occupants about 1899 and will shortly be demolished. View No. 2 shows the Church mainly,as observed northward across an excavation on the south side of the Street. Moses Ling's handbook of New York (1892), on page 351, states that Church of the Strangers at No. 299 Mercer Street was purchased by Commodore Vanderbilt in 1870 and presented to Dr. Deems, a former M.E. clergyman from North Carolina. His preaching attracted great attention and he organized this church in 1868 without organic
connections with any other denomination.
